		<img src="icon_posticon.gif" border="0" hspace="3"><font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;09/26/2002&nbsp;:&nbsp; 05:52:10</font>

		&nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&amp;id=5105"><img src="icon_profile.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Show Profile" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>
        
			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=5105')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&amp;REPLY_ID=76550&amp;TOPIC_ID=8608&amp;FORUM_ID=6&amp;CAT_ID=1&amp;Forum_Title=The+Great+Necro+Talks+2002&amp;Topic_Title=So+what+would+we+like+to+see+for+Necros+in+PoP%3F&amp;M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         Some things i see badly lacking from the current Necromancer spell list on test:</P><P>1)Saryrn's Kiss: This spell should return more Hit Points to the caster.  In its current form it is not much of an upgrade to Vexing Mordinia.  This spell should probably be returning at least 1500-1700 Hit Points to the caster considering the HUGE number of Hit Points that will be lost to Seduction of Saryrn.</P><P>2) No upgrade to Touch of Night.  This is a no brainer, see above.</P><P>3) Darkness upgrade has too long of a casting time and costs too much to cast.  First of all, Necromancers do not use the darkness line for damage output.  It is used for its snare component.  Giving us a new darkness spell that does not last any longer, or cast any faster is not an upgrade.  The damage it does is trivial, as ideally the spell never wears off and is constantly overwritten until mob is dead.  So for most of us Necros 425 mana is way too much to spend on snare that lasts no longer than our level 29 version, which casts 2 seconds faster and for 325 less mana, and has the exact same resist rate as Embracing Darkness.  What necromancers want as an upgrade to our darkness line is what Shadowknights are proposed to receive as Festering Darkness: short cast time, longer duration, low mana cost.  Again, the damage from this spell is trivial, it will only be used for its snare component.</P><P>4)Touch of Death: We do not need a pet only heal.  What we should be getting is the logical upgrade to Shadowbond, which by the way I use to heal my pet all the time.  Whatever form this spell ends up taking, it should not be pet only.. we already have a pet LoH skill that just needs to have its reuse timer lowered by about 1hr 30min to make it actually worthwhile to buy.</P><P>5)Dark Plague is barely an upgrade at all.  Considering this is the final DoT spell we will see at level 65 (until the next expansion), and it does LESS damage over a TWICE the number of ticks as Funeral Pyre, i fail to see where this earns its spot in our spell book at its current proposed level.  If it does 3k+ damage in 2min, that would be a REAL upgrade.</P><P>6) Death's Silence is not an upgrade to Screaming Terror, and it should be.  We do not need an undead only mez spell.  While the stats on the spell are very impressive, the fact it is undead targetable only makes its use EXTREMELY limited in practical situations where you are encountering equal or greater numbers of live mobs versus undead mobs. </P><P>7) No upgrade to Exile Undead.  While someone on the Dev Team seems to feel that we need a very powerful undead only mez spell, they have failed to notice that we are missing a logical upgrade to one our staple spell lines.  Clerics are proposed to get a massively powerful upgrade to Exile with a 4:1 ratio.  Necromancers do not require a spell THAT poweful, but we should be getting some kind of upgrade in this spell line.</P><P>8) Where is our Cold version of Funeral Pyre?  This is something that is not only logical, but has precedent in our spells already (Ignite/Chill Bones).  As it stands, when we face Fire resistant mobs we are are at a serious disadvantage over other classes that carry both fire and cold based damage spells.</P><P>Those are the most glarinly obvious problems i can see from where we stand at this moment.  There are some other more minor issues i have with certain spells, but the above 8 points cover the worst of it.  </P><P>Thank you for taking the time to read, and i hope it has provided some insight from a long time player's prospective.  I understand all the above mentioned spells/ideas are still in test phase and subject to change at any time, and that is why i wish to voice my opinions now.</P><P>Vtyn<BR>Warlock<BR>Heaven and Earth</P><P></P><P></P><P>Edited by - VtynofSaryrn on 09/26/2002  05:57:52<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
      </tr>

